COVID-19 Survey Analysis for UNICEF

Select plots I created for UNICEF’s Risk Communication and Community Engagement program, studying drivers of COVID-19 perceptions and behaviors to inform information dissemination campaigns. The project involved creating up to 70 unique plots for each of 6 survey rounds, plus trends over time and regression analysis to determine causality. The data was entirely categorical and required extensive cleaning and preparation for analysis.

plot_1_function <- function(variable, plot_title, round, no, ns, yes) {
  
  # Select variable and prepare breakdown by key demographics
  
  plot_data <- round6 %>%
    filter(round == round) %>%
    mutate(all = "All") %>%
    dplyr::select(all,
                  province,
                  gender,
                  age,
                  locality,!!as.symbol(variable),
                  Wt) %>%
    pivot_longer(
      cols = c("all",
               "province",
               "gender",
               "age",
               "locality"),
      names_to = "group",
      values_to = "demographic"
    ) %>%
    group_by(group, demographic) %>%
    mutate(Sum_Wt = sum(Wt), percent = Wt / Sum_Wt * 100) %>%
    group_by(group, demographic,!!as.symbol(variable)) %>%
    summarise(percent = sum(percent)) %>%
    mutate(
      group = case_when(
        group == "age" ~ "Age",
        group == "all" ~ "",
        group == "gender" ~ "Gender",
        group == "locality" ~ "Locality",
        group == "province" ~ "Province"
      ),
      group = factor(group, levels = c(
        "", "Gender", "Locality", "Province", "Age"
      ))
    ) %>% group_by(!!as.symbol(variable)) %>% mutate(ylim = max(percent) + 5)
  
  ## Plot data
  
  ggplot(data = plot_data,
         aes(
           x = percent,
           y = demographic,
           fill = !!as.symbol(variable)
         )) + geom_col(width = 0.9) + geom_text(
           aes(label = paste(round(percent), "%", sep = "")),
           size = 4,
           hjust = -0.1,
           color = "black"
         ) + scale_fill_manual(values = c(orange,
                                          yellow,
                                          green)) + facet_grid(
                                            rows = vars(group),
                                            cols = vars(!!as.symbol(variable)),
                                            scales = "free",
                                            space = "free",
                                            switch = "y"
                                          ) + labs(title = plot_title,
                                                   subtitle = paste("Round", round, sep = " ")) +
    theme(
      panel.background = element_blank(),
      panel.spacing.y = unit(2, "lines"),
      axis.text.x = element_blank(),
      axis.text.y = element_text(size = 10, color = "black"),
      axis.ticks = element_blank(),
      axis.title = element_blank(),
      legend.position = "none",
      strip.background = element_blank(),
      strip.placement = "outside",
      strip.text.x = element_text(size = 14, hjust = 0),
      strip.text.y.left = element_text(
        size = 14,
        hjust = 0,
        angle = 360
      ),
      plot.title = element_text(size = 15),
      plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 14),
      plot.title.position = "plot"
    ) + geom_blank(aes(x = 0)) +
    geom_blank(aes(x = ylim))
  
  write.csv(plot_data,
            paste("R6_visuals/csv/", variable, "_plot.csv"),
            row.names = FALSE)
  ggsave(
    paste("R6_visuals/svg/", variable, "_plot.svg", sep = ""),
    last_plot(),
    device = "svg",
    width = unit(13.33, "in"),
    height = unit(7.5, "in")
  )
  ggsave(
    paste("R6_visuals/png/", variable, "_plot.png", sep = ""),
    last_plot(),
    device = "png",
    width = unit(13.33, "in"),
    height = unit(7.5, "in")
  )
  
}

Case for Reduction in PSF Import Duty

The following analyses and visualizations are part of the knowledge capital I have developed for APTMA, regularly used in reports, briefs and media pieces to advocate for rationalization of the PSF import duty.

Despite being one of the top exporters of textiles and apparel, Pakistan’s share in the international market is very low. One reason for this is low product diversification; 67% of exports are cotton-based, while the global market is evenly divided among cotton, man-made fibers, and other materials. MMF-based manufacturing is not competitive due to an 18% import duty (CD+ADD) on polyester staple fiber, a crucial raw material. Additionally, three local producers exploit this protection to artificially inflate domestic PSF prices.

import.share.fun <- function(year = 2021) {
  
  read.csv(
    paste(
      "data/BACI_HS07_V202301/BACI_HS07_Y", year, "_V202301.csv",
      sep = ""
    )
  ) %>% 
    as_tibble() %>% 
    mutate(
      k = as.character(k),
      k = if_else(
        str_length(k) == 5, paste("0", k, sep = ""), k
      )
    ) %>% filter(
      as.numeric(str_sub(k, 1, 2)) >= 50 & as.numeric(str_sub(k, 1, 2) <= 63)
    ) %>% 
    left_join(
      read.csv("data/BACI_HS17_V202301/country_codes_V202301.csv") %>% 
        rename(
          "i" = "country_code",
          "country.i" = "country_name_abbreviation",
          "EU.i" = "EU"
        ) %>% select(i, country.i, EU.i),
      by = "i"
    ) %>% 
    left_join(
      read.csv("data/BACI_HS17_V202301/country_codes_V202301.csv") %>% 
        rename(
          "j" = "country_code",
          "country.j" = "country_name_abbreviation",
          "EU.j" = "EU"
        ) %>% select(j, country.j, EU.j),
      by = "j"
    ) %>% filter(
      country.j == "USA" | country.j == "China" | 
        country.j == "United Kingdom" | EU.j == 1
    ) %>% group_by(country.j, k) %>% 
    summarise(v = sum(v)) %>% 
    left_join(
      read.csv("data/fabric_classes.csv") %>% 
        pivot_longer(cotton:artificial) %>% 
        filter(!is.na(value)) %>% 
        mutate(k = as.character(value), class = name) %>% 
        select(k, class),
      by = "k"
    ) %>% mutate(
      class = if_else(
        str_sub(k, 1, 2) == "52", "cotton", if_else(
          str_sub(k, 1, 2) == "54" | str_sub(k, 1, 2) == "55", "mmf",
          if_else(is.na(class), "Other", class)
        )
      )
    ) %>% mutate(
      class = str_to_title(class),
      class = case_when(
        class == "Mmf" ~ "MMF",
        class == "Artificial" ~ "MMF",
        class == "Synthetic" ~ "MMF",
        class == "Cotton" ~ "Cotton",
        class == "Other" ~ "Other"
      )
    ) %>% 
    group_by(country.j, class) %>% summarise(v = sum(v)) %>% 
    ungroup() %>% 
    mutate(
      country.j = if_else(
        country.j == "USA", "USA", if_else(
          country.j == "China", "China", if_else(
            country.j == "United Kingdom", "United Kingdom", "EU"
          )
        )
      )
    ) %>% 
    group_by(country.j, class) %>% 
    summarise(v = sum(v)) %>% 
    group_by(country.j) %>%  mutate(percent = v/sum(v) * 100) %>%
    ungroup() %>% mutate(year = year)
  
}

raw.import.shares <- lapply(c(2007:2021), import.share.fun) # Calculate annual import shares for 2007-2021

## Export share calculations for select countries ----

export.share.fun <- function(year = 2021) {
  
  read.csv(
    paste(
      "data/BACI_HS07_V202301/BACI_HS07_Y", year, "_V202301.csv",
      sep = ""
    )
  ) %>% as_tibble() %>% 
    mutate(
      k = as.character(k),
      k = if_else(str_length(k) == 5, paste("0", k, sep = ""), k)
    ) %>% filter(
      as.numeric(str_sub(k, 1, 2)) >= 50 & 
        as.numeric(str_sub(k, 1, 2) <= 63)
    ) %>% 
    left_join(
      read.csv("data/BACI_HS17_V202301/country_codes_V202301.csv") %>% 
        rename(
          "i" = "country_code",
          "country.i" = "country_name_abbreviation",
          "EU.i" = "EU"
        ) %>% select(i, country.i, EU.i),
      by = "i"
    ) %>% 
    left_join(
      read.csv("data/BACI_HS17_V202301/country_codes_V202301.csv") %>% 
        rename(
          "j" = "country_code",
          "country.j" = "country_name_abbreviation",
          "EU.j" = "EU"
        ) %>% select(j, country.j, EU.j),
      by = "j"
    ) %>% filter(
      country.i == "Pakistan" | country.i == "India" | 
        country.i == "Bangladesh" | country.i == "Viet Nam" |
        country.i == "China" | country.i == "Indonesia" | country.i == "Turkey"
    ) %>% group_by(country.i, k) %>% 
    summarise(v = sum(v)) %>% 
    left_join(
      read.csv("data/fabric_classes.csv") %>% 
        pivot_longer(cotton:artificial) %>% 
        filter(!is.na(value)) %>% 
        mutate(k = as.character(value), class = name) %>% 
        select(k, class),
      by = "k"
    ) %>% mutate(
      class = if_else(
        str_sub(k, 1, 2) == "52", "cotton", if_else(
          str_sub(k, 1, 2) == "54" | str_sub(k, 1, 2) == "55", "mmf",
          if_else(is.na(class), "Other", class)
        )
      )
    ) %>% mutate(
      class = str_to_title(class),
      class = case_when(
        class == "Mmf" ~ "MMF",
        class == "Artificial" ~ "MMF",
        class == "Synthetic" ~ "MMF",
        class == "Cotton" ~ "Cotton",
        class == "Other" ~ "Other"
      )
    ) %>% 
    group_by(country.i, class) %>% summarise(v = sum(v)) %>% 
    group_by(country.i, class) %>% 
    summarise(v = sum(v)) %>% 
    group_by(country.i) %>% mutate(percent = v/sum(v) * 100) %>%
    ungroup() %>% mutate(year = year)
  
}

raw.export.shares <- lapply(c(2007:2021), export.share.fun) # Calculate annual export shares for 2007-2021

## Herfindahl-Hirchman Index Graph ----

data <- read.csv( # read BACI 2021 bilateral trade flows
  paste(
    "data/BACI_HS07_V202301/BACI_HS07_Y", 2021, "_V202301.csv",
    sep = ""
  )
) 

# Prepare data and calcualte HHI 

p.data <- data %>%
  as_tibble() %>% 
  mutate(
    k = as.character(k),
    k = if_else(
      str_length(k) == 5, paste("0", k, sep = ""), k
    )
  ) %>% filter(
    as.numeric(str_sub(k, 1, 2)) >= 50 & as.numeric(str_sub(k, 1, 2) <= 63)
  ) %>% 
  left_join(
    read.csv("data/BACI_HS17_V202301/country_codes_V202301.csv") %>%
      rename(
        "i" = "country_code",
        "country.i" = "country_name_abbreviation",
        "EU.i" = "EU"
      ) %>% select(i, country.i, EU.i),
    by = "i"
  ) %>% group_by(country.i, k) %>% 
  summarise(v = sum(v)) %>% group_by(country.i) %>% 
  mutate(total.export = sum(v)) %>% 
  mutate( # Calculate HHI
    export.share = v/sum(v) * 100,
    export.share.sq = export.share*export.share
  ) %>% group_by(country.i) %>% 
  summarise(hhi = 1/sum(export.share.sq)) %>% 
  mutate( # variable to highlight select countries in plot
    color = if_else(
      country.i == "Pakistan", "A", if_else(
        country.i == "Bangladesh", "B", if_else(
          country.i == "India", "C", if_else(
            country.i == "China", "D", if_else(
              country.i == "Viet Nam", "E", "F"
            )
          )
        )
      )
    )
  ) %>% ungroup() %>% mutate(
    hhi.norm = (hhi - min(hhi))/(max(hhi) - min(hhi)) # Normalize HHI between 0-1
  ) %>% left_join(
    data %>% 
      as_tibble() %>% 
      mutate(
        k = as.character(k),
        k = if_else(
          str_length(k) == 5, paste("0", k, sep = ""), k
        )
      ) %>% filter(
        as.numeric(str_sub(k, 1, 2)) >= 50 & as.numeric(str_sub(k, 1, 2) <= 63)
      ) %>% 
      left_join( # Add country names
        read.csv("data/BACI_HS17_V202301/country_codes_V202301.csv") %>% 
          rename(
            "i" = "country_code",
            "country.i" = "country_name_abbreviation",
            "EU.i" = "EU"
          ) %>% select(i, country.i, EU.i),
        by = "i"
      ) %>% group_by(country.i) %>% 
      summarise(v = sum(v)),
    by = "country.i"
  ) %>% arrange(-v)

## Make HHI plot ----

  ggplot(
    p.data %>% filter(row_number() <=25),
    aes(x = hhi.norm, y = reorder(country.i, hhi))
  ) + geom_col(aes(fill = color)) + 
    theme(
      panel.background = element_blank(),
      legend.position = "off",
      axis.ticks = element_blank(),
      axis.title.y = element_blank()
    ) +
    scale_fill_manual(
      values = c(green, red, yellow, blue, grey, "lightgrey")
    ) + labs(
      x = "Textiles & Apparel Export Diversification Index",
      caption = "Source: APTMA calculations using BACI trade data"
    ) + geom_text(
      aes(label = paste("$", round(v/1000000), " bn", sep = ""), x = 0.01),
      hjust = 0, color = "white", size = 3
    )
  
  ggsave("plots/new_gov_agenda/hhi.png", h = 5, w = 6.27, units = "in")
  ggsave("plots/new_gov_agenda/fig_3.svg", h = 5, w = 6.27, units = "in")

Pakistan Stock Exchange Web Scraper

A function to scrape key information about firms listed on the Pakistan Stock Exchange. It’s ready to run; just copy and paste it into your R console.

library(tidyverse)
library(rvest)
library(shinyjs)

# A function that pulls tables on key information including profit, revenue, management, recent notices issued,
# etc., about firms listed on the Pakistan Stock Exchange
# Uses company symbol to visit PSX company profile and pull all html tables

scrape.psx <- function(symbol){ 
  print(paste("Starting ", symbol, sep = "")) 
  link = paste(
    "https://dps.psx.com.pk/company/",
    symbol, sep = "")
  page <- read_html(link) 
  tables <- page %>% 
    html_elements(css = ".tbl__body") %>%
    html_table()
  print(paste(symbol, " Complete", sep = ""))
  return(tables)
  Sys.sleep(5) 
}

scrape.psx("SCBPL") # Try function for Standard Chartered Bank Pakistan
